ce-based legal remedies that accurately address implicit and unintentional forms of discrimination, to replace the weak, tepid, and largely irrelevant legal remedies currently available.Our continued failure to fashion an effective response that purges the effects of implicit bias from American health care, Matthew argues, is unjust and morally untenable. In this book, she unites medical, neuroscience, psychology, and sociology research on implicit bias and health disparities with her own expertise in civil rights and constitutional law. In a time when the health of the entire nation is at risk, it is essential to confront the issues keeping the health care system from providing equal treatment to all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination in medical carexUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezUnited States. 0aHealth Status Disparities. 0aHealth and racexUnited States. 0aHealth and racezUnited States. 0aHealthcare Disparities. 0aMedical policyxUnited States. 0aMedical policyzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxMedical carexUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxMedical carezUnited States. 0aRacism. 7aLAW / Medical Law & Legislation.2bisacsh  aHealth disparities.  ablack health.  aequal treatment.  ahealth care for the poor.  ahealth care system.  ahealth education.  aimplicit bias.  amedical care.  amedical education.  amedical racism.  amedical treatment.  aminority health.  apoverty and health care.  aracial injustice.  asystemic injustice.  asystemic racism.  aurban health.  aurban medicine.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479899630.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479899630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479899630/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LA